            "title": "Many Voices, Many Traumas: An Analysis of Memoirs of Homosexual Holocaust Survivors",
            "date": {
                "start": {
                    "month": 9,
                    "day": null,
                    "year": 2019
                },
                "end": {
                    "month": 7,
                    "day": null,
                    "year": 2020
                }
            },
            "description": "A part of Sophia College for Women's highly selective, 'Excellence in Arts Program (EXAP)' this seminar paper explores memoirs as a literary device for the expression of trauma, oppression & conflict. It delves into the Nazi Volk Ideology and the subsequent persecution of millions of Jews and other minorities, including homosexuals through three memoirs. The literary analysis focuses on the representation of trauma, its processing, and the struggle for survival. The paper uses insights from trauma studies, particularly from trauma theorist Cathy Caruth to understand literature as a tool for coping with traumatic events, a tool for continued resistance and a representation of trauma and survival.",
